**Debounce delays the execution of a function until after a certain amount of time has passed since the last time it was called.**

```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// Example: Debounce a search input to avoid excessive API calls
const input = document.getElementById('search');
input.addEventListener('input', debounce((event) => {
  console.log('Searching for:', event.target.value);
}, 300));
```

**Explanation:** The `debounce` function ensures the search is only triggered after the user stops typing for 300ms.
